{
  "texts": [
    "Inspection of Table 3 and Figure 7 suggests that the NEnKF is able to give inferences consistent with SMC 2 and the ground truth parameter values that generated the data.",
    "For data set D 1 (d = 5), fewer ensemble members are required for NEnKF compared to state particles for SMC 2, leading to an increase in computational efficiency of around a factor of 3.5.",
    "For data set D 2 (d = 10) and a single run of each scheme, SMC 2 required 4762 state particles whereas NEnKF required just 249 ensemble members, leading to a difference in computational efficiency of approximately a factor of 19 (2737 minutes versus 147 minutes, for SMC 2 versus NEnKF).",
    "Not surprisingly, as the observation dimension increases, both schemes require increased numbers of state particles / ensemble members, N, although the relative increase is much smaller when using NEnKF.",
    "It is evident from Figure 7, that NEnKF triggers the resample-move and dynamic increasing of N steps less often than SMC 2."
  ]
}